	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64482037"><p><div class="quote"><p>A "frozen" vendor kernel is an insecure kernel.</p><span class="substr"> </span></div><p>Maybe. But that's the safe way to bet.</p><p><div class="quote"><p>The number of known bugs in a "frozen" vendor kernel grows over time.</p></div><p>Not really. The bugs were always there. They just haven't been found yet.

</p><p>The whole back-porting of only "pristene" patches is bound to break down. Because as time goes by, the newer patches become more dependent on the new features continually being added to the kernel. And the work to back port becomes more difficult and error prone, introducing its own  bugs. Eventually, one adds more bugs than they patch.
</p><p>Keeping up with the current kernels new features is a never</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64482037">

</div>
</div>

